      <p> Sami began playing the modern oboe aged 12 and began to fall in
        love with the instrument and music. She began her further education
        at Birmingham Conservatoire in 2009, where she was taught by Richard
         Weigall, Jenni Philips and George Caird. It was here that she was
         introduced to the baroque oboe by Gail Hennessy. After a very
         difficult and frustrating start with the baroque oboe, she was
         fortunate to receive a grant to buy her own instrument. It was then,
          that she instantly fell in love with the instrument and her passion
          for the music flourished. <br>
In 2016 she graduated from The Royal Conservatory of The Hague, in the
Netherlands, where she studied historical oboe under Frank de Bruine. <br>
Currently, she is a professional freelance oboist performing with many
ensembles such as CBMV and RCM's collaboration directed by Sir Roger Norrington,
 Musical and Amicable Society, The Armade Players, Instruments of Truth andTime,
 Eboracum, Oxford Bach Soloists, Phoenix Baroque Orchestra, Leeds Baroque,
 Benslow Music Trust, Den Haags Vocale and many more. She maintains a professional
  career throughout the UK and Europe. In January 2014, she performed the Fasch
  Oboe Concerto in D with Birmingham Conservatoire Baroque Orchestra Directed and
   led by Lucy Russel.</p>
